        "itemName": "“Delaying Conveniences” in the 1950’s",
        "itemSubhead": "Tillman Ward Discusses not having Hot Water or Television",
        "itemDescription": "Tillman Ward, interviewed here, grew up in Vine City right on the site of the present day Ashby Street MARTA station. Tilman’s father built the duplex himself, renting out one side to fund his children's college education. This scrimping for the benefit of future generations was a common experience in the neighborhood in the 1950’s and 60’s, used by many African American families to create housing that white developers were often unwilling to build.  Black owner-builders commonly saved money to buy vacant land, then gradually built their own houses as they could afford, often foregoing amenities like electricity in the meantime.  When owners could not complete the work themselves, they typically turned to Black building tradesmen like carpenters and masons, keeping economic gains within communities.",
