        "itemSubhead": "July, 1988: State, County and City Argue over the Terms of the Dome",
        "itemDescription": "The first Georgia Dome deal was spearheaded by a group of investors, the “Stadium Corporation,” with support from the board of the Georgia World Congress Center. While the Dome was ultimately built on what the state considered “abandoned railroad land,” the expansion of the World Congress Center, which was wrapped up in the deal, included the use of eminent domain to seize and raze 126 homes in the Lightning Community and relocate those families. The community was outraged, as were the churches and prominent members of city council who also spoke up against the early plans. In response, a ten million dollar trust fund was set up to help build affordable housing in the area. Many were still upset about the agreement but plans proceeded. While many governing bodies had roles to play in the stadium deal, this interview with then-Fulton County Commissioner Nancy Boxill focuses  on the state’s. The financing for the estimated $158 million needed to build the Dome required that 1/3 of the cost come from the city and county hotel-motel tax.",
