        "itemSubhead": "1997-2008: Hardship on the Westside",
        "itemDescription": "After the excitement of the 1996 Olympics receded, residents of the Westside noticed little economic benefit from the influx of money that came in during the surge of development. Instead, by 2001 another jobs recession was hurting the area and a housing boom was spurring bricks and mortar investment but little substantial change. In 2002, a massive flood put parts of the Westside under six feet of water. When the Great Recession hit in late 2007 and the housing bubble burst, buildings and houses built during the boom were left empty. Homeowners were underwater on mortgages (many of which were fraudulent) and renters were evicted from homes owned by absentee landlords. The area was again plagued by water damage when a 2008 tornado hit and residents were reminded of how living in  one of the city’s lowest lying areas could have dangerous consequences.",
