        "itemSubhead": "New Pockets of Activism and Resistance",
        "itemDescription": "The 2008 foreclosure crisis hit the United States hard. Between 2007 and today, more than 5 million American households have experienced foreclosure. This waterfall of foreclosures, disproportionately impacted working and middle class Americans, particularly people of color. And a number of the mortgages and evictions were fraudulent. With fraud also came resistance and activism. Atlanta’s Occupy Our Homes emerged from the Occupy and housing justice movements to help working class Atlantans fight for the right to fair housing. In 2012 the group helped the Higher Ground Empowerment Center, a historic church in Vine City, and a Vine City homeowner, win the right to stay in their church and home. Part of the post-Occupy resurgence of direct action, Occupy Our Homes Atlanta shows that new pockets of activism can crop up and shift the activist landscape, even if only momentarily. ",
