        "itemName": "2017 Georgia Dome – Georgia Supreme Court Case",
        "itemSubhead": "English Avenue and Vine City Residents take the City to Court",
        "itemDescription": "In February 2014, when the Georgia legislature voted to validate the use of bonds tied to the Fulton County hotel-motel tax to finance the Georgia Dome, a group of English Avenue and Vine City residents filed objections. The residents, Mamie Moore, Reverend W.L. Cottrell, Tracy Bates, John H. Lewis III and Joe Henry Beasley then embarked on a more than a year long legal battle ending in a loss at the Georgia Supreme Court. The group argued that the 2010 state law authorizing extension of the existing Atlanta hotel-motel tax was unconstitutional and that the city’s development wing, Invest Atlanta, was not legally allowed to issue revenue bonds for property that they do not own. The Georgia Supreme Court did not rule in the residents’ favor and claimed that the hotel-motel tax could be used to fund the stadium because the city and county would “directly benefit from an increase in tourism” from the Dome. This statement was made despite widespread agreement amongst U.S. economists that stadiums do not directly increase city revenues. In this 2015 interview, Mother Moore, one of the parties in the lawsuit, outlines her reasons for pursuing this legal action. ",
