        "itemSubhead": "Looking Back to help Shape a Better Future",
        "itemDescription": "Today, Atlanta’s Westside is again in a period of intense development and neighborhood groups are organizing in response. Georgia Tech is extending their campus into the area; the Atlanta Housing Authority recently received a thirty million dollar award from HUD to rebuild mixed-income housing at the sites of former housing development projects; the Atlanta Beltline Inc. is promising to build up the Westside trail; the Blank Foundation, Chik-Fil-A Foundation and Invest Atlanta are embarking on a “place-based” approach to redevelopment along with the recently created Westside Future Fund, a nonprofit established and led by mayor Kasim Reed, high-powered Atlanta CEO’s and university presidents, which promises to coordinate the planning, fund-raising and revitalization efforts across the Westside. As past waves of development, housing construction and community-based resistance and activism have shown, the success or failure of future attempts at change making depend on many factors, a number of them deeply connected to sweeping structural and historical mechanisms outside of any one group’s control. Listening to and learning about the ways that structural forces have impacted the lived experiences, memories, hopes and dreams of English Avenue and Vine City residents is a central component of learning from history. It is our hope that this exhibit has helped, in some small way, contribute to this effort.",
